description.plain:
Ashton Nicole Casey, better known as Ashnikko, was born on February 19, 1996, in Oak Ridge, North Carolina. Her stage name Ashnikko is a portmanteau of her first name Ashton and her middle name Nicole.

The London-based rapper, singer and songwriter is known for her rebellious and daring songs with themes of sexuality and female empowerment. Influenced by the likes of feminist musicians like M.I.A., Björk, and Nicki Minaj, Ashnikko fuses hip-hop with a punky electro-pop sound that is native to the English capital.

Due to her upbringing in the ultra-conservative North Carolina, Ashnikko’s early musical diet consisted exclusively of country music and some occasional Slipknot records. Ashnikko spent most of her teen years in eastern Europe after her parents moved to Estonia and then Latvia when she was only thirteen.
A very liberal and creative teen in nature, Ashnikko spent her days doodling and slowly making her first steps toward her imminent career as a rapper who doesn’t necessarily mince her words. She started her musical endeavors with a diss track about one of her classmates over Lil Kim’s “Black Friday” beat.

Upon reaching adulthood, Ashnikko finally managed to break free of her conservative chains and began a new life in London where she enjoyed a wild party life and where she continued to pursue her creative notions through music.

On the 31st of July in 2016, she uploaded her first song “KROKODIL” to SoundCloud. Since then, Ashnikko has released two solo EPs, Hi, It’s Me and Unlikeable, along with a collaborative EP Sass Pancakes with Raf Riley.

After having successfully figured out her unique style by the time Sass Pancakes dropped, Ashnikko first explored the topic of female empowerment on her second EP Unlikeable and continued to stand up for women in and out of the industry on her third EP Hi, It’s Me. In an interview with 1883 Magazine, she said:

I got bullied a lot because I did music. It’s quite a patriarchal society there, a lot of men were offended by my presence. […] Doing something different is uncomfortable, regardless what you do differently – you always get hated especially as a woman. But regardless, its always more rewarding to be yourself.

Her song “STUPID” featuring Atlanta-based rapper Yung Baby Tate garnered massive popularity on the lip-syncing app Tik Tok months after its initial release, having accumulated over two million posts by the end of October 2019. The viral song marked her first entry on Billboard, peaking at #1 on the Billboard Hot 100 Bubbling Under Charts.

songs.title: STUPID

description.plain:
“STUPID” is a song off of Ashnikko’s second solo EP, Hi, It’s Me.

The song features Atlanta based producer and artist Yung Baby Tate, and follows a lot of the themes of the other tracks on the EP: Break-up anthem, empowerment type stuff.

The song started going viral on the video-sharing app Tik Tok (formerly musical.ly) in mid-2019.

The song’s music video was released on October 22nd, 2019. It features a slasher-like theme to fit the Halloween spirit.

songs.title: Slumber Party

description.plain:
As an open pansexual, Ashnikko explores her relationship with women in “Slumber Party” with a story about a girl she fell for who ultimately broke her heart.

In an Instagram story with Spotify UK, a fan asked if the song was based on a true story, to which Ashnikko replied sarcastically:

What do you think?

Ashnikko is known for basing all of her songs off of personal life, using her albums as “therapy.”

songs.title: Daisy

description.plain:
In a similar fashion to Ashnikko’s previous two singles “Tantrum” and “Cry,” “Daisy” serves as another haunting pop banger in Ash’s discography in which she dismantles the patriarchy and defies female stereotypes. On the song, Ash reinterprets the image of the daisy, which has been used as a symbol for innocence and weakness in literature since Celtic times, to point out the fact that they, much like herself, are able to withstand harsh environments and bloom in the darkest of places. Additionally, some species of daisies close at night. Ash contrasts this by saying that she “blossoms in the moonlight,” further illustrating how she defies expectations.

The song marks her third official single of 2020. She has performed the song live on several occasions in late 2019 and early 2020.
